Student Athletes Committed to Honor otherwise known as SACH acts as a liaison between the Honor Committee and the athletic community and we create an open and honest forum for discussion of Honor and how it relates to student athletes. God is moving!! The past couple days have been incredible. It's a small world and there have been moments where God is the only one that could make these occurrences happen. Just on Tuesday Night our flight from Munich to Paris got cancelled we were able to talk with European customer service and get on the next flight just an hour later on standby. We landed safely in Paris and took a bus to the station nearest our Hostel. We ended up running into a 25 year old man named Carlos who was from Yukatan and he was as lost as we were in such a new city. His friend he was meeting in Paris was a day late and he didn't have a place to stay. He ended up coming with us to our Hostel which was full and the owner of the hostel allowed him to sleep on the floor in our room. All day the next day he came with us to the Eiffel Tower and we shared stories we laughed and we didn't care about the language barrier or our life circumstances. For that moment we were One. He left that night as family and left us with a saying  Mi Casa es tu Casa   My house is your house . Later that night a young man named Anurug got to the Hostel but it was full and he pleaded for a spot the owner allowed him. I just started talking to him in the lobby and we conversed and talked about traveling experiences. He was from Tanzania. He ended up being by himself in Paris and We invited him to come along with us the next day to the Palace of Versailles. It was a beautiful day and again we shared stories and culture. He invited us to Tanzania and will continue to be a friend for a life time. It is these moments that we put differences aside to just be as God calls us to be One.

Today is #worldmentalhealthday 1 in 5 Americans struggle with mental disorders each year and I am one of them. (*gasps* omg how could she share that on social media) Anxiety and depression can make life a whirlwind of confusion and emotional exhaustion. Somedays it makes you wake up and literally just say  NO.  It is absolutely nothing to be ashamed of you showed up today that counts. But for those of you who aren't around me on a daily basis or aren't more than acquaintances how would you know that I was dealing with anxiety regularly if I hadn't written this post? Exactly. Mental disorders occur in people of all colors shapes sizes religions political views ages and backgrounds. So let's end the stigma and start the conversations. No one should feel like they are experiencing the effects of mental disorders alone. Chances are there are a lot more people in your life than you might think who are dealing with these things on a day to day basis. So if there's anything you take away from this it's plz be kind to everyone you meet and always make taking good care of yourself a top priority!!! ğŸ‰ğŸ’•

We tend to fall into cyclic patterns of overthinking and self-criticizing that ruin our perception of life sometimes to the point of no longer wanting it. I've lost friends to suicide and almost lost many more the past few years. Suicide and suicide ideation are severe issues that often go unaddressed.  So let's go back to when we were little kids and we weren't afraid to ask for help when we needed it. Let's try to judge less both ourselves and others and breathe a little more deeply. Let go of the internship that you didn't get the test you bombed or the ass that didn't text you back.  Go ahead and scream cry punch a hole in the wall (security deposit tho) make pickle voodoo dolls like from Lilo & Stitch (personal fav) - whatever you need to do to get through it. Just don't hesitate to reach out. Don't ever give up on yourself. #WorldSuicidePreventionDay

4. Self. I sacrificed a lot for my dream of being a rocket scientist but as people around me earned summer jobs I was afraid. I feared I wasn't good enough and as I searched for something external to tell me I was I lost my identity. I started trying to fit the part:  What should I being doing?  Rather than  What do I want to do?  Recently a quote resonated with me: at the end of the day all we have is ourselves. No one can convince you of how amazing you are except yourself so take time for yourself do what you want and above all: love yourself. Your self expression might just put you the place you want to be. Trust me I'm a NASA engineer (intern). || Thank you to the people who have given me that advice for months: you were right but I wasn't ready to listen--you know who you are.

3. Brother. We weren't always good siblings but we figured it out. I couldn't be more thankful for the mutual respect we have for each other but I admire your respect of self. The best advice you ever gave me was simply  Do what you want.  At the end of the day you take life into your own hands make mistakes succeed fail but you always stay sure in yourself. Thank you for teaching me to love myself and above all: make my own luck. #nationalsiblingday

Dawg Camp has introduced me to a part of myself I did not even know existed. My story at the University of Georgia started with Dawg Camp Adventure in the summer of 2014 and I am so happy to say it's been a part of my life since. The impact that my fellow staff members and campers have had on me is immeasurable. I find new ways to fall in love with this school every single year because of Dawg Camp! Fall in love with UGA all over again and experience the magic that is Dawg Camp. The app closes in a couple of hours so APPLY!!! dawgcamp.uga.edu

What does UGA mean to me?  Home. I moved to the Georgia about six years ago from Washington state halfway through my high school career. Although my new school was a wonderful place I found it difficult to fit in and truly be myself. So when I came to UGA I was looking for somewhere I could grow. Somewhere to find a community. Somewhere to call a home.  I have found that here at Georgia. I have been challenged intellectually and have had the blessing of being inspired by my peers. I am excited that I get to constantly enjoy what I have chosen to study. How lucky am I that my mind is blown every day I go to class! I have received such a rounded education here-I am confident in my abilities to contribute and give back to the communities that have given so much to me.  In the end the organization endorsements don't matter. The campaigning the stickers the buttons the profile pictures all of those are temporary. They will fade with time. However the endless amount of support and love that I have felt is not. No matter the outcome of this week I will always remember this feeling. And no matter who is crowned I know that they will be absolutely deserving because this Court is full of incredible individuals who will all change the world in their own ways! And we all owe it to the University of Georgia. What an honor. Vote for who you truly believe deserves this! https://uga.campuslabs.com/engage/
